    {
        "content": "<p>Maybe classical geometers? Those who consider a sphere only as a hypersurface with extrinsic geometry, I would guess. Of the references listed on the mathworld page, only a couple of them look like they'd use this weird indexing, one of which is a Dover book from the 1950s.</p>",
        "id": 278400270,
        "sender_full_name": "David Michael Roberts",
        "timestamp": 1649498017
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The other is Coxeter, but I notice that the \"supporting\" quote from him doesn't actually justify the \"n-sphere\" terminology.</p>",
